TITLE: Configuring Style Dictionary with JSON Configuration File
DESCRIPTION: Defines a standard JSON configuration for the Style Dictionary framework specifying source token files, build platforms, output formats, and build directories. Dependencies include the Style Dictionary npm package, and the config must be referenced by the CLI (`--config`). Inputs are paths to token JSON files and platform definitions; outputs are generated platform-specific style files. Platform entries illustrate transforms and file destinations; additional options allow further customization.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/README.md#_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{\n  \"source\": [\"tokens/**/*.json\"],\n  \"platforms\": {\n    \"scss\": {\n      \"transformGroup\": \"scss\",\n      \"buildPath\": \"build/\",\n      \"files\": [\n        {\n          \"destination\": \"scss/_variables.scss\",\n          \"format\": \"scss/variables\"\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    \"android\": {\n      \"transformGroup\": \"android\",\n      \"buildPath\": \"build/android/\",\n      \"files\": [\n        {\n          \"destination\": \"font_dimens.xml\",\n          \"format\": \"android/fontDimens\"\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining Design Tokens (Original Format) in JSON
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to define color design tokens using the original Style Dictionary format in a JSON file (`tokens.json`). Each token node is an object containing a `value` attribute (the token's actual value) and a `type` attribute (classifying the token, e.g., 'color'). This structure allows Style Dictionary to process and transform tokens appropriately.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/info/tokens.md#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "colors": {
    "font": {
      "base": { "value": "#111111", "type": "color" },
      "secondary": { "value": "#333333", "type": "color" },
      "tertiary": { "value": "#666666", "type": "color" },
      "inverse": {
        "base": { "value": "#ffffff", "type": "color" }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Programmatically Extending StyleDictionary with ES Modules/Objects (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This example illustrates how to use advanced configuration with Style Dictionary in Node.js by importing enums and configuring platforms with transform groups and output formats. It uses both ES Module and CommonJS require syntax, accepts a configuration object, and defines how tokens should be processed (e.g., for SCSS). Inputs include the configuration object, and the output is the appropriately generated asset files. Requirements include Node.js  and a project structure with design token sources. This allows for full programmatic control over style transformation and output.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/README.md#_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import { formats, transformGroups } from 'style-dictionary/enums';

const StyleDictionary = require('style-dictionary').extend({
  source: ['tokens/**/*.json'],
  platforms: {
    scss: {
      transformGroup: transformGroups.scss,
      buildPath: 'build/',
      files: [
        {
          destination: 'variables.scss',
          format: formats.scssVariables,
        },
      ],
    },
    // ...
  },
});

StyleDictionary.buildAllPlatforms();
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Configuring Token Source Files in JSON5
DESCRIPTION: Example Style Dictionary configuration (`config.json`) using JSON5 syntax to specify the source files containing design tokens. The `source` property uses a glob pattern (`tokens/**/*.json`) to include all JSON files within the `tokens` directory and its subdirectories. This configuration is used by Style Dictionary to locate token definitions.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/info/tokens.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: json5
CODE:
```
// config.json
{
  source: ['tokens/**/*.json'],
  //...
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Style Dictionary Extend with Custom Platforms - JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to import the Style Dictionary, initialize it with a config file, and extend it with custom platform options. This snippet demonstrates importing enums for formats and transform groups, creating an initial Style Dictionary instance, and then extending it with source and platform definitions (e.g., SCSS with custom transforms and destinations). The resulting 'sdExtended' instance can be used to build tokens and platforms. Requires Style Dictionary and relevant enums, as well as file system access if using 'config.json'.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/api.mdx#_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import StyleDictionary from 'style-dictionary';
import { formats, transformGroups } from 'style-dictionary/enums';

const sd = new StyleDictionary('config.json');

const sdExtended = await sd.extend({
  source: ['tokens/*.json'],
  platforms: {
    scss: {
      transformGroup: transformGroups.scss,
      buildPath: 'build/',
      files: [
        {
          destination: 'variables.scss',
          format: formats.scssVariables,
        },
      ],
    },
    // ...
  },
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Building Tokens Using Style Dictionary JavaScript API (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to import the StyleDictionary package, initialize it with a configuration, and build all platforms programmatically. Requires Node.js (ESM syntax), the 'style-dictionary' package, and a 'config.json' file with token definitions and build targets. This code returns a Promise due to the use of async/await for asynchronous operations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/getting-started/using_the_npm_module.md#_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import StyleDictionary from 'style-dictionary';

const sd = new StyleDictionary('config.json');
await sd.buildAllPlatforms();
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Referencing (Aliasing) Token Values in JSON
DESCRIPTION: Example JSON structure demonstrating how to reference the value of another design token using curly braces and dot notation (`{size.font.medium}`). This creates an alias, making the `value` of `size.font.base` dynamically linked to the value of `size.font.medium`. This technique promotes consistency and reduces redundancy in token definitions.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/info/tokens.md#_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "size": {
    "font": {
      "small": { "value": "10" },
      "medium": { "value": "16" },
      "large": { "value": "24" },
      "base": { "value": "{size.font.medium}" }
    }
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining Design Tokens (DTCG Format) in JSON
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates defining color design tokens using the Design Token Community Group (DTCG) specification format within a JSON file (`dtcg-tokens.json`). This format uses `$value` for the token value and `$type` at the group level (or optionally at the token level). Style Dictionary v4 supports both this format and the original format.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/info/tokens.md#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "colors": {
    "$type": "color",
    "font": {
      "base": { "$value": "#111111" },
      "secondary": { "$value": "#333333" },
      "tertiary": { "$value": "#666666" },
      "inverse": {
        "base": { "$value": "#ffffff" }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

