TITLE: Modernizing Design Token Type Assignment in tokens.json (JSON)
DESCRIPTION: Shows the updated recommended structure for a design tokens JSON file. Each token now has an explicit 'type' property (e.g., 'color'), instead of relying on CTI (category/type/item) structure. This aligns with the Design Tokens Community Group standard. No dependencies; example demonstrates self-contained assignment of type to each token. Input/output: JSON used for token source.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/version-4/migration.md#_snippet_20

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "color": {
    // <-- this no longer needs to be "color" in order for
    // the tokens inside this group to be considered of type "color"
    "red": {
      "value": "#FF0000",
      "type": "color"
    }
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Getting Platform Tokens - TypeScript
DESCRIPTION: Provides the type definition for 'getPlatformTokens', a function that asynchronously exports a dictionary of design tokens for a particular platform after all transformations and reference resolutions. The function takes a platform name (must exist in config) and an options object to control cache usage. Returns a Promise resolving to a Dictionary object. Requires an extended Style Dictionary instance with defined platforms. Limitation: If cache is false or the platform has not been processed, tokens are generated anew.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/api.mdx#_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
type getPlatformTokens = (platform: string, opts: { cache?: boolean }) => Promise<Dictionary>;
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Initializing Style Dictionary with a Config File in NodeJS
DESCRIPTION: This JavaScript snippet demonstrates the basic usage of the Style Dictionary Node module. It imports the `StyleDictionary` class, instantiates it by providing the path to a configuration file (`config.json`), and then asynchronously invokes `buildAllPlatforms()` to process the design tokens according to the specified configuration. This requires the `style-dictionary` npm package and a valid `config.json` file.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/getting-started/installation.mdx#_snippet_13

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import StyleDictionary from 'style-dictionary';

const sd = new StyleDictionary('config.json');
await sd.buildAllPlatforms();
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing a Custom Style Dictionary Format using createPropertyFormatter (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to register a custom format named 'myCustomFormat' in Style Dictionary. It utilizes the `createPropertyFormatter` helper function, configured with options passed from the format function (`outputReferences`, `dictionary`) and set to use the standard CSS format (`propertyFormatNames.css`), to process all design tokens (`dictionary.allTokens`). The resulting formatted strings are joined by newlines to create the final output.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/Utils/format-helpers.md#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import { propertyFormatNames } from 'style-dictionary/enums';

StyleDictionary.registerFormat({
  name: 'myCustomFormat',
  format: function ({ dictionary, options }) {
    const { outputReferences } = options;
    const formatProperty = createPropertyFormatter({
      outputReferences,
      dictionary,
      format: propertyFormatNames.css,
    });
    return dictionary.allTokens.map(formatProperty).join('\n');
  },
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Extending and Building StyleDictionary in Node.js
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates basic usage of Style Dictionary within a Node.js script, utilizing CommonJS require syntax to load and extend the configuration from 'config.json'. The 'buildAllPlatforms' method is then called to generate assets for all configured targets. Prerequisites are Node.js and that 'style-dictionary' and a configuration file are available in the project. Input parameters are the path to the configuration file, and output is processed according to the configuration rules.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/README.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const StyleDictionary = require('style-dictionary').extend('config.json');

StyleDictionary.buildAllPlatforms();
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Enabling Output References in Style Dictionary Config (JSON)
DESCRIPTION: This JSON configuration snippet shows how to enable reference output for the 'css/variables' format in Style Dictionary. Setting `outputReferences: true` within the file's 'options' object instructs Style Dictionary to maintain the original token references (e.g., using CSS variables) in the output file instead of resolving them to their base values.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/Hooks/Formats/index.md#_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
// config.json
{
  "source": ["tokens.json"],
  "platforms": {
    "css": {
      "transformGroup": "css",
      "files": [
        {
          "destination": "variables.css",
          "format": "css/variables",
          "options": {
            // Look here 👇
            "outputReferences": true
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining Design Tokens in JSON
DESCRIPTION: Defines design tokens for colors and font sizes using the JSON format. It includes nested structures for organization, token values, types (e.g., 'color', 'fontSize'), and comments. References to other tokens (e.g., `{colors.base.red}`) are used to maintain consistency.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/examples/basic.mdx#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "colors": {
    "base": {
      "gray": {
        "light": { "value": "#CCCCCC", "type": "color" },
        "medium": { "value": "#999999", "type": "color" },
        "dark": { "value": "#111111", "type": "color" }
      },
      "red": { "value": "#FF0000", "type": "color" },
      "green": { "value": "#00FF00", "type": "color" }
    },
    "font": {
      "base": { "value": "{colors.base.red}", "type": "color" },
      "secondary": { "value": "{colors.base.green}", "type": "color" },
      "tertiary": { "value": "{colors.base.gray.light}", "type": "color" }
    }
  },
  "size": {
    "font": {
      "small": {
        "value": "0.75",
        "type": "fontSize",
        "comment": "the small size of the font"
      },
      "medium": {
        "value": "1",
        "type": "fontSize",
        "comment": "the medium size of the font"
      },
      "large": {
        "value": "2",
        "type": "fontSize",
        "comment": "the large size of the font"
      },
      "base": {
        "value": "{size.font.medium}",
        "type": "fontSize",
        "comment": "the base size of the font"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining a Token Filter Object in Style Dictionary - JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows how to create a filter object for use with Style Dictionary. The filter object includes a filter callback that excludes tokens whose source file ends with 'core.json'. The filter supports asynchronous execution, making it suitable for advanced filtering scenarios. Required dependency: Style Dictionary library; 'myFilter' can then be registered via Style Dictionary's API, and 'token' and 'options' parameters allow contextual logic.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/Hooks/filters.md#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const myFilter = {
  name: 'my-filter',
  // async is optional
  filter: async (token, options) => {
    return !token.filePath.endsWith('core.json');
  },
};
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Building StyleDictionary with CLI (Bash)
DESCRIPTION: This command shows how to trigger the build process for Style Dictionary using its CLI in a project's root directory. It requires a 'config.json' file to exist and can incorporate additional flags for configuration or selective platform builds. Outputs generated style files according to configuration. No external dependencies except for Node.js and a properly installed Style Dictionary.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/README.md#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: bash
CODE:
```
$ style-dictionary build
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Running Style Dictionary Build via CLI
DESCRIPTION: Executes the Style Dictionary build command using `npx` to ensure the package is available locally or fetched. This command processes the token files defined in the source configuration and generates platform-specific outputs based on the `config.json` settings.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/examples/basic.mdx#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: bash
CODE:
```
npx style-dictionary build
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Registering a Custom Output Format in Style Dictionary (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates registering a custom output format with `StyleDictionary.registerFormat`. This example registers a format using the predefined `formats.json` name (imported from `style-dictionary/enums`). The format function receives the dictionary, platform options, and file details, and returns a JSON string representation of the `dictionary.tokens`. Requires the `style-dictionary` package for the `formats` enum.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/api.mdx#_snippet_23

LANGUAGE: js
CODE:
```
import { formats } from 'style-dictionary/enums';

StyleDictionary.registerFormat({
  name: formats.json,
  format: function ({ dictionary, platform, options, file }) {
    return JSON.stringify(dictionary.tokens, null, 2);
  },
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining Tokens with References and Custom Attributes (JSON)
DESCRIPTION: This JSON snippet demonstrates a more complex token structure involving references and custom attributes (`darken`). `color.danger` references `color.red` and has a `darken` attribute, while `color.error` references `color.danger` with its own `darken` attribute. This setup is used to illustrate how custom transitive transforms can modify values based on references and additional token data.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/Hooks/Transforms/index.md#_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
```json title="tokens.json"
{
  "color": {
    "red": { "value": "#f00" },
    "danger": { "value": "{color.red}", "darken": 0.75 },
    "error": { "value": "{color.danger}", "darken": 0.5 }
  }
}
```
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Structuring Hierarchical Design Tokens in JSON for CTI Pattern
DESCRIPTION: Displays a JSON structure for organizing design tokens using the Category/Type/Item (CTI) hierarchy. Each token object includes a value for use in style definitions. Dependencies: Style Dictionary. Input: hierarchical token declarations; output: a structured token object tree processed by transforms or exported in various formats.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/README.md#_snippet_12

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{\n  \"size\": {\n    \"font\": {\n      \"base\": { \"value\": \"16\" },\n      \"large\": { \"value\": \"20\" }\n    }\n  }\n}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Defining Style Dictionary Platforms Configuration - JSON
DESCRIPTION: This JSON configuration file specifies the source token files and defines output platforms (e.g., SCSS and Android) with their respective transforms, formats, destinations, and actions. Dependencies include having Style Dictionary set up in your project. Key parameters include 'source' for token files, 'platforms' to configure outputs, and options like 'transformGroup', 'buildPath', and 'files'. The expected input is arrays of design tokens, and output is formatted resource files for each platform.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/reference/config.md#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: json
CODE:
```
{
  "source": ["tokens/**/*.json"],
  "platforms": {
    "scss": {
      "transformGroup": "scss",
      "prefix": "sd",
      "buildPath": "build/scss/",
      "files": [
        {
          "destination": "_variables.scss",
          "format": "scss/variables"
        }
      ],
      "actions": ["copy_assets"]
    },
    "android": {
      "transforms": ["attribute/cti", "name/snake", "color/hex", "size/remToSp", "size/remToDp"],
      "buildPath": "build/android/src/main/res/values/",
      "files": [
        {
          "destination": "style_dictionary_colors.xml",
