TITLE: Creating a Custom Style Dictionary Format to Output Token References (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This JavaScript snippet demonstrates a function for a custom Style Dictionary format. It iterates through all design tokens and uses the `usesReferences` utility to check if a token's original value contains a reference (alias) to another token. If it does, `getReferences` is used to obtain details about the referenced token(s), and the output string replaces the resolved reference value with the actual name of the referenced token, thus preserving the alias in the final output (e.g., exporting JavaScript constants).
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/examples/advanced/variables-in-outputs/README.md#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import { usesReferences, getReferences } from 'style-dictionary/utils';

//...
function({ dictionary }) {
  return dictionary.allTokens.map(token => {
    let value = JSON.stringify(token.value);
    // the `dictionary` object now has `usesReferences()` and
    // `getReferences()` methods. `usesReferences()` will return true if
    // the value has a reference in it. `getReferences()` will return
    // an array of references to the whole tokens so that you can access their
    // names or any other attributes.
    if (usesReferences(token.original.value)) {
      const refs = getReferences(token.original.value, dictionary);
      refs.forEach(ref => {
        value = value.replace(ref.value, function() {
          return `${ref.name}`;
        });
      });
    }
    return `export const ${token.name} = ${value};`
  }).join(`\n`)
}
```

