TITLE: Adapting Custom Formats for Asynchronous fileHeader (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates how custom formatters need to be updated for Style Dictionary v4. The `formatter` function itself can now be `async`, and the `fileHeader` utility function (imported from `style-dictionary/utils`) is now asynchronous and must be awaited (`await fileHeader({ file })`). This allows `fileHeader` functions defined in the configuration to perform asynchronous operations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/amzn/style-dictionary/blob/main/docs/src/content/docs/version-4/migration.md#_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
```js title="build-tokens.js" del={9,13} ins={10,14-15}
import StyleDictionary from 'style-dictionary';

// yes, this is another breaking change, more on that later
import { fileHeader } from 'style-dictionary/utils';

StyleDictionary.registerFormat({
  name: 'custom/css',
  // this can be async now, usually it is if you use fileHeader format helper, since that now always returns a Promise
  formatter: function ({ dictionary, file, options }) {
  format: async function ({ dictionary, file, options }) {
    const { outputReferences } = options;
    return (
      fileHeader({ file }) +
      // this helper is now async! because the user-passed file.fileHeader might be an async function
      (await fileHeader({ file })) +
